[[File:Singapore Road Signs - Temporary Sign - Detour.svg|thumb|right|100px|Detour sign used in Singapore]]
[[File:MUTCD M4-9L.svg|thumb|right|100px|Detour sign used in the United States]]
A '''detour''' or ([[British English]]: '''diversion''') is a (normally temporary) route taking traffic around an area of prohibited or reduced access, such as a [[construction]] site. Standard operating procedure for many roads departments is to route any detour over roads within the same jurisdiction as the road with the obstructed area.<ref>Example: {{cite news |first=Joseph |last=Dits |coauthors= |title=Capital Ave. to be closed at railroad tracks in Mishawaka for a week |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/southbendtribune/access/2327206901.html?FMT=ABS |work=[[South Bend Tribune]] |publisher= |date=2011-04-19 |accessdate=2011-04-20 |quote=The state will erect signs that take car traffic on a detour all the way through downtown South Bend &ndash; a longer detour than local residents could figure out &ndash; because the state has to use state roads, said InDOT spokesman Jim Pinkerton. |format=fee required }}</ref>

On multi-lane [[highway]]s (e.g., [[freeways]], [[Limited-access road|expressways]], city streets, etc.), usually [[contraflow lane reversal#Highway reconstruction|traffic shifts]] can replace a detour, as detours often congest turn lanes.
