{{refimprove|date=July 2012}} {{Infobox person |name = Pieter Dirkszoon Keyser |image = |image_size = |caption = |birth_date = 1540 |birth_place = [[Emden]], [[Germany]] |death_date = 11 September {{death year and age|1596|1540}} |death_place = [[Sunda Strait]], [[Indonesia]] |other_names = Petrus Theodorus |known_for = |occupation = [[Navigator]] |nationality = [[Dutch Republic|Dutch]] }}
'''Pieter Dirkszoon Keyser''', sometimes '''Petrus Theodorus''' (c. 1540 in [[Emden]] &ndash; 11 September 1596 in [[Banten]]), was a [[Dutch Republic|Dutch]] navigator who mapped the [[southern hemisphere|southern sky]].
==Voyages and star observation== Little is known of Keyser's life outside of his astronomical observations and East Indies voyages.<ref name=knobel>{{cite journal|last=Knobel|first=E. B.|title=On Frederick de Houtman's catalogue of southern stars, and the origin of the southern constellations|journal=[[Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society]]|date=March 1917|volume=77|pages=414–432|url=http://articles.adsabs.harvard.edu//full/1917MNRAS..77..414K/0000414.000.html|accessdate=12 July 2012|bibcode = 1917MNRAS..77..414K|doi=10.1093/mnras/77.5.414}}</ref> After several trips, {{citation needed span|text=one to [[Brazil]], and one to [[Novaya Zemlya|Nova Zembla]]|date=November 2012}} Keyser participated as the chief navigator and head of the steersmen for the first Dutch voyage to the [[East Indies]] (the "Eerste Schipvaart"), which left [[Texel]] with four ships on 2 April 1595 under [[Cornelis de Houtman]]. He had been trained by cartographer [[Petrus Plancius]] in mathematics and astronomy. Plancius, a key promoter to the Dutch East Indies expeditions, had instructed Keyser to map the skies in the [[Southern Celestial Hemisphere|southern hemisphere]], which were largely uncharted at the time.<ref name=knobel /><ref name=startales>{{cite book|last=Ridpath|first=Ian|title=Star Tales|date=1988|publisher=Lutterworth|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-0718826956|page=9|url=http://www.ianridpath.com/startales/startales1c.htm}}</ref> When the fleet finally was able to obtain fresh supplies at [[Madagascar]] on 13 September, 71 of the 248 sailors had died, most of [[scurvy]]. The surviving crew stayed for several months on the island, to recover and make repairs, at which point Keyser probably made most of his celestial observations. He was aided in this by [[Frederick de Houtman]] and Vechter Willemsz. After leaving Madagascar, it took another four months (February to June 1596) for the ships to reach [[Sumatra]] and finally [[Bantam (city)|Bantam]] on [[Java]]. Trade negotiations went sour, perhaps caused by [[Portugal|Portuguese]] instigators, perhaps by inexperience, and the crew was forced to find drinking water and other supplies on Sumatra across the [[Sunda Strait]]. Keyser apparently died during this crossing. On 14 August 1597, 81 survivors made it back to Texel, including de Houtman, who probably delivered Keyser's observations to Plancius.{{citation needed|date=July 2012}}
==Constellations== From the observations of the expedition, Plancius created a celestial globe in late 1597, published by [[Jodocus Hondius]], showing twelve new constellations of the southern sky that have become accepted among the [[88 modern constellations|standard constellations]] codified by modern astronomers. The majority were named after various animals that 16th century explorers had encountered (e.g. Bird of Paradise, Chameleon, Toucan, Flying Fish). [[Willem Janszoon Blaeu]] copied these constellations on a 1602 globe and created a new globe in 1603 incorporating further observations made by de Houtman on a second voyage to the East Indies. [[Johann Bayer]] included these new southern constellations in his influential 1603 star atlas ''[[Uranometria]]'', crediting them to "Petrus Theodori" (Pieter Keyser),<ref>{{cite book |last=Kanas |first=Nick |date=2009 |title=Star Maps: History, Artistry, and Cartography |edition=2nd |publisher=Springer |page=119 |isbn=978-1-4614-0916-8}}</ref> but not acknowledging their earlier publication. Bayer is therefore often mistakenly credited for introducing them.<ref>{{cite web|title=Johann Bayer's Southern Star Chart|last=Ridpath|first=Ian|url=http://www.ianridpath.com/startales/bayer%20southern.htm|accessdate=7 April 2015}}</ref>
Keyser is commemorated by [[minor planet]] (10655) Pietkeyser.<ref name=JPL>{{cite web|title=10655 Pietkeyser (9535 P-L)|url=http://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/sbdb.cgi?sstr=10655|work=Solar System Dynamics|publisher=Jet Propulsion Laboratory, California Institute of Technology|accessdate=12 July 2012}}</ref>
